threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a malicious IoT botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt families. It exhibits several definitive malicious behaviors: network discovery using SSDP (Simple Service Discovery Protocol) to find vulnerable devices, process enumeration via /proc to identify and kill competing malware (sub_4044c0 and sub_405150), and multiple built-in DDoS attack routines (TCP/UDP flooding). It contains strings associated with the 'Netis' router exploit ('Self Rep Fucking NeTiS') and uses browser User-Agent spoofing to mask its network activity. Additionally, it features a shell execution component (/bin/sh) and uses simple XOR-style obfuscation for its internal command strings.
